    "decidedAt": "2026-04-19T00:00:00Z",
    "rationale": "The FEA model ensemble for the non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw ASTM F1717 compression-bending COU is accepted at MRL 5 with one offset. Twelve of 13 V&V 40 credibility factors meet or exceed their required levels, with output comparison achieving level 5 (E/uval < 1.0 for all three QoIs). The single shortfall — Test conditions (achieved 3, required 4) — arises from testing at a single crosshead displacement rate. The offset rationale below documents why this shortfall does not undermine the overall credibility determination: inter-laboratory replication across two independent facilities, combined with a sensitivity analysis confirming <3% QoI variation across the plausible friction and material property uncertainty space, provides sufficient confidence that the single-rate test condition does not introduce material bias. The provenance chain is complete from raw bench test data through FEA input decks to validation results, with all datasets archived under DOI-referenced data packages. The decision is grounded in the structured evidence assembled across all 13 factors and is consistent with the ASME V&V 40 framework for a Class II device at medium model influence and medium decision consequence.",
    "hasOffsetRationale": [
      {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/offset/nagaraja-cou1-tc-offset",
        "type": "OffsetRationale",
        "name": "Offset rationale for Test conditions shortfall (achieved 3, required 4)",
        "description": "The Test conditions factor achieved level 3 rather than the required level 4 because testing was conducted at a single crosshead displacement rate (5 mm/min) without variation of loading rate or fixture configuration. This shortfall is offset by three compensating factors: (1) inter-laboratory replication across two independent accredited test facilities demonstrated protocol reproducibility with <2.3% inter-lab QoI variability; (2) the ASTM F1717 standard specifies a single quasi-static loading rate as the normative test condition for this device class, meaning the single-rate approach is protocol-conformant rather than a study design limitation; (3) a parametric sensitivity analysis varying crosshead displacement rate from 1 mm/min to 25 mm/min (via strain-rate-dependent material model) showed <1.5% change in all three QoIs, confirming rate insensitivity within the quasi-static regime. Taken together, these compensating factors provide confidence equivalent to a level 4 assessment for this factor in the context of the overall credibility determination."
      },
      {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/decision/nagaraja-cou1-mrl5-accepted-v3/offset/nagaraja-cou1-tc",
        "type": "OffsetRationale",
        "refersToFactor": "https://uofa.net/synth/factor/nagaraja-cou1-tc",
        "justification": "Placeholder offset rationale (Phase 2.5 v0.5.11 corpus regen) for 'Test conditions' factor shortfall on this Accepted decision. The W-AR-02 rule's intent is to flag Accepted-despite-shortfall findings that are NOT documented; structurally well-formed but not substantively meaningful. Real-world V&V 40 cases (e.g., Nagaraja et al. 2024 §4) record the offsetting evidence here."
      }
    ]
  },
